<font color="#FF0000">HMONG - THE FORGOTTEN PEOPLE</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jun 29 18:16:42 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Gerald,<br><br>
It is sad to see that America has forgotten about its allies, like my people--the Hmong.  I have uncles who fought and died as a result of the Secret War in Laos.  Indeed, they fought for our freedom but it was also the Americans who went there to promise  and encourage them to fight until the end.  The promise--according to the Hmong soldiers who fought for the CIA--was that if the Hmong should win the war, they would be made leaders of Laos.  If they should lose the war, the Americans would help them.  Off course, this promise was not written down because like everything else, it was all &quot;secret!&quot; Yet, when the war ended in April, 1975 and the communists took over the country, the Americans abandoned the Hmong.  Tens and thousands of Hmong died trying to escape Laos as a result.  Those who were fortunate enough crossed the Mekong River to Thailand and lived in filthy refugee camps for years where many died from diseases and starvation before they were eligible to come to the United  States.  <br><br>
The war has changed the lives of the Hmong forever.  There are still people who have bomb pieces lodged in their bodies.  Many could not work.  Some are blinked or disabled.  Others are physically and mentally scared.   Yet, these people still have to face a new economic war in the U.S.  This war began with the signing of the new welfare reform law which will take effect this July, 1997.  It will limit benefits to non-U.S. citizens and force abled-body people to seek work.  I strong agreed that abled-body people should find work but, what about those elderly Hmong veterans and their wives or children who cannot?  They are old and most are not U.S. citizens; the majority still don't know how to speak, read or write English.  What are they going to do if their federal assistance is cut-off?  <br><br>
I think this is just another betrayal on the Hmong.  I heard recently that congress has agreed to grand citizenship and eligibility benefits to those Hmong who are qualified.  However, I don't know if this is true because I don't know the true source; it may be rumors only.  In California where 50% the Hmong in the United States live, the Hmong were labeled as &quot;lazy people who don't want to work and just want to make babies.&quot;  Well, I am a Hmong and am insulted by these words.  I think all cultures have lazy people but I don't think I am one nor all my people.  I have hopes and dreams just like most Americans.  I came here when I was a teen and spoke no English.  I struggled through high school and college to learn English.  Even now, my English is not yet perfect but I have a job and am living the American dream.  What makes it so difficult for other Hmong is their personal backgrounds.  In Laos, the Hmong lived in an agrarian society and very few had any schooling.  In fact, they did not even had a written language until missionaries invented one for them in 1953.  It is also the language,  culture, and the availability of jobs here that make it difficult for many Hmong to earn a living.  <br><br>
Currently, in America Hmong are making good progress.  I still remember in the early 1980s when many Hmong worked as janitors and/or factory workers.  Now, we have successful Hmong businessmen, bankers, insurance agents, social workers, teachers, professors, lawyers, dentists, and physicians alike.  The number of Hmong students in higher education has also increased from a few to couple hundreds in cities like Fresno, California or St. Paul, Minnesota.  Though this progress is still slow and small, it just shows that we Hmong will succeed as any other immigrant groups who came before us in the past 100 years or so.  <br><br>
To this end, if America should choose to harm the Hmong people instead of extending their hands to help them get through their hardships, America is only trying to hurt its own citizens--the new Hmong Americans.<br><br>

